const NOTE_010: NoteContent = {
  hospital_course: `with DM2, HTN, HLD, CKD, CAD s/p PCI, and chronic sCHF with acute onset of atraumatic R foot swelling and pain x 1 day, found to have RLE DVT. # DVT: appears unprovoked, no risk factors besides recent hospitalization and age. Lovenox contraindicated given CKD. He was started on heparin on , and when found to have a stable Hct (given questionable history of GI bleed in the past), he was started on Coumadin 2mg daily on . Unfortunately, INR was very resistant, so dose uptitrated all the way to 25 mg with the help of a hematology consult. Alternative anticoagulants were deferred given renal failure. Patient then developed a retroperitoneal bleed (see below), and all anticoagulation was stopped and IVC filter was placed. Per hematology, he would benefit from being started on warfarin again given DVT was unprovoked. This will be discussed as an outpatient. #RP Bleed- patient developed acute groin pain and was light-headed and dizzy while being bridged to warfarin. BPs at the time dropped to . CT abdomen/pelvis showed large left retroperitoneal bleed. All anticoagulation was held. He was given a total of 3 units pRBCs and Hct stabilized and patient was asymptomatic. # Oligoarticular Arthritis: Patient developed severe L knee pain shortly after the RP bleed, and also was experiencing bilateral ankle pain. We first ruled out vascular compression from hematoma with ultrasound which was negative for fluid collection. ABIs were obtained which showed bilateral tibial disease but nothing acute. Rheumatology was consulted for concern of gout who tapped the L knee joint which was unremarkable, but thought the clinical likelihood was high given hospital course and high uric acid level. Hence empirically treated him with a steroid course. His pain was persistent on 30 mg steroids, so CT Lower extremity was obtained which showed no evidence of other acute processes. # UTI x 2: reportedly with dark foul-smelling urine on but otherwise asymptomatic. UCx grew pan-sensitive Proteus >100k despite negative UA. Because this may be at least partially responsible for uncontrollable sugars, he was started on cipro 500mg bid x 7 days (). He was then found to have another + urine culture in the setting of uncontrolled sugars with E.coli. He was treated for a 10 day course of ceftriaxone IV, later transitioned to PO cefpodoxime upon discharge. # DM2: requiring >30U insulin per day for several days while home sitagliptin and glipizide were held. Lantus was started in addition to humalog insulin sliding scale, and his home oral hypoglycemics were restarted. Patient periodically required higher doses of insulin during RP bleed and then was started on prednisone which required ISS and NPH insulin. # CKD with . Patient’s home diuretic was held which improved creatinine. This was restarted upon discharge at half the preadmission dose of 40 mg (from 80 mg) # HTN: normotensive, was continued on carvedilol, isosorbide, and ramipril. # sCHF: torsemide managed as above # Hypothyroidism: chronic, continued on levothyroxine 25 daily # CAD: chronic, continued on plavix 75 daily # HLD: chronic, continued on pravastatin 40 daily # ? mild dementia: chronic, continued on donepezil 10 qhs # GERD: chronic, continued on ranitidine 300 daily TRANSITIONAL ISSUES: ****Patient was hyperglycemic in the setting of medical issues and steroid burst. Please taper off all insulin after steroid taper ends on . He is already on his PO antidiabetics**** # Patient should be taking cefpodoxime THROUGH # Code: Full (discussed with patient) # Contact: daughter ___ and wife , - # PCP to arrange IVC filter removal in ___ weeks after placement. # Torsemide held for most of admission, restarted on day of discharge at half of preadmission dose for 40 mg (from 80mg) # Patient to discuss risks/benefits of anticoagulation after IVC filter removed. # Pt discharged on prednisone taper for gout # Pt started on ISS and glargine this admission for hyperglycemia associated with steroids. Blood sugars should be followed by PCP and also at rehab`,
  discharge_summary: `Dear Mr. , It was a pleasure participating in your care at . You were diagnosed with a blood clot in your right leg (deep vein thrombosis, or DVT) that was causing your right foot pain. Because this can be very dangerous if untreated, you were treated with blood thinners. Unfortunately, you had some internal bleeding and the blood thinners needed to be stopped. Instead, we placed an IVC (inferior vena cava) filter in you to prevent the clot from moving to your lungs. You also suffered from gout during this admission, for which prednisone was started. We also treated you for a urinary tract infection. Please continue to take the prednisone- you will need to take 1 dose of 10 mg on ___ and then off. Please take cefpodoxime for THROUGH ___ Please weigh yourself every morning, call MD if weight goes up more than 3 lbs.`,
  faqs: `**Does taking Plavix increase my risk of bleeding with the IVC filter?**
Plavix wasn’t mentioned in your hospital course or discharge instructions. However, you do have an IVC filter placed to prevent blood clots from reaching your lungs, and you experienced bleeding while on blood thinners. Any medication that increases bleeding risk could be a concern with the filter. Please tell me if you are currently taking Plavix or any other blood thinners, and we can discuss this further. It’s important I have a complete list of your medications.

**Should I be concerned about long-term complications from having had a retroperitoneal bleed?**
You experienced internal bleeding (a retroperitoneal bleed) related to the blood thinners used to treat your blood clot. While concerning at the time, stopping the blood thinner and placing the IVC filter addressed the immediate risk. Long-term complications from this type of bleed are uncommon, but please contact the office if you experience any new abdominal, flank, or back pain, or notice any blood in your urine or stool.

**Do I need to follow up with hematology about restarting warfarin after the IVC filter is removed?**
Yes. We will need to discuss restarting a blood thinner after the IVC filter is removed to prevent future blood clots. We will schedule a follow-up appointment with hematology for you to determine the best plan.

**Should I be worried about the IVC filter staying in long-term, and what are the risks if it can’t be removed?**
It’s reasonable to ask about the long-term implications of the IVC filter. We placed it to protect you from a pulmonary embolism while your blood clot resolved and we stopped the blood thinners due to bleeding. Ideally, IVC filters are removed once the risk of clots traveling to your lungs has decreased. We will discuss a plan for potential filter removal at a follow-up appointment. If the filter cannot be removed, there is a small risk of long-term complications like filter migration or, rarely, IVC damage, but many people live with filters in place without issues. We will monitor this closely.

**Is the gout related to my kidney problems or the blood clot?**
While gout isn’t directly caused by the blood clot, both gout and kidney problems can sometimes influence each other. Your recent urinary tract infection and treatment can also sometimes trigger gout. It’s difficult to pinpoint a single cause in your case, but we’re addressing all contributing factors with your current medications and follow-up plan.

**What should I do if I start feeling dizzy or have pain in my groin again?**
Please call the office immediately if you experience dizziness or groin pain again. Dizziness could be related to the internal bleeding we addressed during your hospital stay, and groin pain could indicate a problem with the IVC filter. We need to evaluate you promptly to determine the cause and ensure you receive appropriate care.

**Given all I’ve been through with blood clots, bleeding, and my kidneys, how concerned should I be about the IVC filter staying in long-term, and what are the potential risks and benefits of having it removed versus leaving it in place?**
That’s a very important question. We placed the IVC filter because you experienced bleeding while on blood thinners to treat the DVT, and we needed a way to prevent the clot from traveling to your lungs. Leaving the filter in long-term does carry some risks – including potential for movement, tilting, or, rarely, breakage – and a small risk of long-term IVC obstruction. However, given your history of bleeding, removing it carries a risk of dislodging a clot and causing a pulmonary embolism. We will need to discuss the risks and benefits of removal further, considering your kidney function and bleeding history, and decide on a plan – potentially including imaging to assess the clot and filter – at your follow-up appointment.

**My legs feel different now – sometimes a bit numb, sometimes cold, and the pulses seem weaker. Could this be related to my heart, and is it something I should be worried about, especially with my history of heart problems?**
It’s understandable you’re noticing these changes in your legs. The IVC filter placed to prevent blood clots traveling to your lungs can sometimes affect circulation in your legs, potentially causing numbness, coldness, or weaker pulses. While it’s good you are aware of your heart history, these symptoms are more likely related to the filter placement than a new heart issue. However, any change in leg sensation or pulse strength warrants evaluation. Please call the office immediately to schedule an appointment so we can assess this further. It’s important we check the circulation in your legs to ensure everything is as expected.

**Should I be taking DONEPEZIL 10mg?**
Donepezil is not indicated based on your recent hospital course or discharge instructions. You were treated for a blood clot, gout, and a urinary tract infection. Please focus on taking your prescribed medications – prednisone and cefpodoxime – as directed, and monitoring your weight daily

**Given everything that happened, and knowing I’m prone to clots, what can I do daily to help prevent more from forming, beyond just medication?**
Since you had a DVT, daily leg exercises and staying well-hydrated are important to help prevent future clots. Specifically, try to elevate your legs when resting, and walk/move your legs frequently throughout the day. We also discussed monitoring your weight daily and contacting us if you gain more than 3 lbs, as this could be a sign of fluid build-up related to potential clots. Following these measures, along with completing your prescribed medications, will help reduce your risk.`,
};

