const NOTE_017: NoteContent = {
  hospital_course: `___ w/IDDM, HTN, s/p L ___ and ___ toe amputation w/ hosp ___ for diabetic foot ulcer, third metatarsal shaft osteomyelitis, adjacent abcess with wound culture growing multiple organisms including group B strep, yeast and pseudomonas aeroginosa d/c’d on augmentin in anticipation for definitive treatment with surgery now presenting with L foot swelling, fever/chills, pain . # Third metatarsal shaft ostemolyelitis due to diabetic L foot ulcer w/ expanding soft tissue abscess - failed augmentin rx while awaiting definitive rx (surgery) for osteomyelitis - NAI’s with essentially normal arterial supply - MRI w/ third metatarsal shaft osteomyelitis, 2 cm soft tissue abscess and tenosynovitis of the flexor digitorum longus tendons of the second and third rays extending to the distal mid foot. - wound culture w/ mixed bacterial types, moderate growth of beta streptococcus group B, rare yeast and pseudomonas aeroginosa. - Vancomycin and cefepime for now to cover mutiple organisms in wound including various strep species and pseudomonas - abcess drained and packed by podiatry after admission - f/u cultures of abcess contents - OR on HD2 for ___ met head resections, ulcer excision with primary closure with drain. Pt tolerated procedure well (see op note for details) - Drain pulled POD2 and bivalve cast placed - dsg changes daily; Pt seen and evaluated by ___ - d/c home on POD4 with qd dsg changes, Augmentin, NWB to f/u with Dr. ___ in 1 week. . # IDDM - 50 lantus at night plus ISS as per , give when NPO - cont lisinopril . # HTN: - cont norvasc, metoprolol, lisinopril . # CAD: - cont ACE, statin, BB - holding ASA as above . # FEN/GI - diabetic diet # PPx - SC heparin, PPI # Code - Full # Dispo - pending above`,
  discharge_summary: `Please resume all preadmission medications. You were given an antibiotic and pain medication, please take both as directed. . Keep your dressing clean and dry at all times. You will have nurses perform dressing changes regularly. . You are to remain non weight-bearing on your L foot at all times. Please keep your bivalve cast on at all times as well. Keep your L foot elevated to prevent swelling. . Call your doctor or go to the ED for any increaes in L foot redness, swelling or purulent drainage from your wound. For any nausea, vomiting, fevers greater than 101.5, chills, nightsweats.`,
  faqs: `**Should I continue taking all my heart medications even though I’m on antibiotics for my foot?**
Yes, please continue taking all your regularly prescribed heart medications as directed. Your heart medications are separate from the antibiotics you’ve been given for your foot infection and are important for your overall health. Do not stop any medication without first talking to your doctor.

**What should I do if my foot swelling doesn’t go down with elevation, or if the pain gets worse despite taking the pain medication?**
Call your doctor or go to the Emergency Department. Increasing redness, swelling, or pain despite elevation and medication could indicate a worsening infection or complication from your diabetic foot ulcer and osteomyelitis. We need to evaluate that promptly.

**When should I start taking my aspirin again?**
The discharge instructions do not mention aspirin. Please contact your primary care physician or the prescribing doctor to determine when it is safe to resume your aspirin, as it wasn’t specifically addressed in your post-operative care plan following treatment for your diabetic foot ulcer and osteomyelitis.

**Is the discoloration from the wound healing cause any serious problem? Can you please tell me its side effects? And what are the issues we can face in future due to this problem? And does it have any treatment? Is it true that there is no treatment for this problem and I will get ill sooner due to protein loss, and there is also 20 % chances of kidney failure in the future?**
Discoloration can be part of wound healing, but given your history of a diabetic foot ulcer and osteomyelitis (bone infection), any increased redness, swelling, or drainage from the wound needs to be reported immediately as it could indicate worsening infection. You were prescribed an antibiotic to address the infection, and it’s crucial to take it as directed. While osteomyelitis can be serious, treatment is available and you are currently awaiting surgery to address this. Untreated, chronic osteomyelitis can, unfortunately, lead to complications like continued pain, potential limb dysfunction, and, in rare cases, spread of infection. Chronic infection and poor wound healing can contribute to protein loss and, over many years, can potentially affect kidney function. A 20% chance of kidney failure is not something I can confirm from

**Could it be fungal? Are symptoms different? And if my symptoms are causing no pain could it be something else than an infection?**
Given your history of a diabetic foot ulcer and osteomyelitis (bone infection), and the fact you were treated with antibiotics, a bacterial infection is the primary concern. While fungal infections can occur in the foot, especially with diabetes, your current presentation is more consistent with the infection we’ve been treating. Fungal infections often cause itching, scaling, and discoloration of the nail or skin, but typically aren’t associated with the redness, swelling, fever, or purulent drainage we discussed. The absence of pain doesn’t rule out infection entirely, but it is less common. Swelling and redness in the foot, even without pain, can still indicate an ongoing problem, and you should still follow the instructions regarding elevation and monitoring for any changes. You should still contact us immediately if you notice increased redness, swelling, or drainage.

**Should I be worried about the swelling in my foot getting worse even while taking the antibiotics and keeping it elevated?**
Yes, any increase in swelling, along with redness or drainage from your wound, is a concern and should be reported to your doctor or addressed at the Emergency Department. Even with antibiotics and elevation, worsening swelling could indicate the infection isn’t fully controlled or another complication is developing.

**Is this recurring fever and swelling related to the antibiotics, or is something else going on with my foot infection?**
It’s difficult to say definitively, but given your history of a diabetic foot ulcer and osteomyelitis, and your current symptoms of fever, chills, and swelling, it is more likely related to your foot infection despite being on antibiotics. Antibiotics don’t always completely clear an infection, and sometimes resistance can develop. The instructions to call us or go to the ED for increasing redness, swelling, drainage, fever, chills, or nausea are very important, as it could mean the infection is worsening and needs further evaluation and treatment.

**Kindly see the test report and advice what precautions or medications are required especially regarding my blood sugar control.**
Please resume all pre-admission medications, which I assume includes those for your diabetes. Maintaining good blood sugar control is very important for wound healing, especially with a diabetic foot ulcer and osteomyelitis. Follow your existing diabetes management plan closely. If you notice any signs of infection (increased redness, swelling, drainage from the wound, fever/chills) or if you’re experiencing nausea, vomiting, or night sweats, contact us immediately.

**Is the swelling in my foot a sign the infection is getting worse?**
Yes, increased swelling in your left foot could be a sign the infection is worsening. You were discharged with a diabetic foot ulcer and osteomyelitis, and swelling is listed as a reason for concern. Please elevate your foot and contact us immediately – or go to the Emergency Department – if you notice increased redness, swelling, or drainage from your wound.`,
};

